		<div>Nice work, Sylphan. <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="smile" class="inlineimg" /> If I may, however, I'd like to provide some feedback based on my past experiences with a similar timer design, hope that is OK with you.<br />
<br />
Originally, while brainstorming for version 3 of my timer (my first bar-style timers), I had experimented with an idea somewhat similar to this. I started out by putting the bar animation on the scrollable area, and had the user scroll the animation in order to &quot;reset&quot; the timer, so to speak.<br />
<br />
However, after some testing, I found it easier and faster to &quot;mark&quot; the bar instead of moving the bar into place. With a movable bar, due to scroll area boundaries, the user had to choose the direction that would allow full movement depending on where the animation was at the time. This is not a huge deal, but since timers are often used during frantic combat, not having to decide which way to go saved a bit of time for me. Marking the bar (instead of moving the bar) also had the additional benefit that users can more easily make a mental note of where to place the marker if they are too busy casting, etc. and set the marker later when they have more time. Thus, I opted to go with a movable marker instead of a movable bar animation.<br />
<br />
While designing version 4, I re-visited the same idea once more but eventually abandoned it again, for the following reasons:<br />
<br />
1) Ease and speed of use were the first priority for my new version. With the new button-style marker in version 4, which can be set with a single click, the choice was even more clear than before. There is no clicking-and-dragging involved, as would be required with a scrollable animation. With the new marker, the user simply clicks on the dot to begin timing.<br />
<br />
2) The second priority was conserving screen space. Putting the animation in a scroll area would require a bit of extra room for the scroll bar, whereas the markers can overlap the bar animation, allowing the timers to be more compact.<br />
<br />
3) A third consideration was to allow a single timer to time two instances of the same event. By placing markers at two different points on the bar, it is possible to time two separate mezzes using the same bar animation, for example. This would not be possible with a scrolling animation where the bar itself has to be moved into place.<br />
<br />
The above explains some of the reasoning behind the choices that I made when deciding on a timer design. Even though having a movable timer bar that could be visually &quot;reset&quot; was nice, in the end I personally felt that a marker-based timer was easier/faster to use and provided more benefits for the user.<br />
<br />
I do like what you've done here, though, and I hope you'll keep enhancing and exploring these possibilities further. Your norrathian day timer that is based on the same concept is very, very cool. <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="smile" class="inlineimg" /></div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		<!-- sig -->
			<div>
				__________________<br />
				<b>Arista</b><br />
Level 63 Erudite Enchanter<br />
<i>The Seventh Hammer</i><br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.timermod.com/" target="_blank"><img src="http://www.timermod.com/image/TimerMod.gif" border="0" alt="" /></a><br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.timermod.com/" target="_blank">TimerMod</a> - Timer Utility for EverQuest UI
			</div>
