				</div>
				
				
				
				
				
				<div><a href="http://www.eqinterface.com/list.php?s=85341b51fabfad3ad573dc2699d086ad&amp;skinnerid=820"><img src="/images/misc/badges/author-list-link.gif" width="37" height="39" border="0" alt="Interface Author - Click to view interfaces"></a></div>
				<div>   </div>
			</div>					
		
	</td>
	<td class="alt1">
	
		
			<!-- icon and title -->
			<div class="smallfont">
				<img class="inlineimg" src="images/icons/icon1.gif" alt="Default" border="0" />
				
			</div>
			<hr size="1" style="color:#FFFFFF" />
			<!-- / icon and title -->
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>Thanks Arista <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="smile" class="inlineimg" /><br />
<br />
It's interesting that our timers developed somewhat along the same path.  First with a 2-color timer, where the bar starts as one color (or blank), and gradually fills up with color until full.  Then we both decided to try 1-color timers where a little mark moves from start to end.  Also we both started out with arrows at each end of the timer and later got rid of them.<br />
<br />
1. You seem to be more concerned with the ease of setting the timer.  I'm more concerned with the ease of reading the timer.  Now that you've got the marker to a single click, that's unbeatable speed... click-and-drag can never be as fast as single-click no matter what.  But that little marker is tiny, making it kinda hard to see.  It doesn't serve as a reminder unless you actively check it every few minutes.  I used a set of seven timers for a long time... when each bar and each slider is at a different position it's difficult to tell at a glance if one of them has run out, or will run out soon.  Quite often haste would run out on the group or an illusion (like NDT) would wear off on somebody because I simply hadn't noticed that that particular timer was getting close to its marker.<br />
<br />
I play an enchanter too, so I fully understand how nice it is to set a mark quickly when mezzing stuff.  In fact, that's what I use my dial timer for -- a single click highlights one of the ten numbers.  I also added an extra button to the center of mine, so I could highlight none of the ten numbers.  But I want longer-duration timers to serve as reminders.  Until timers gain the ability to 'ding' or play a sound, the only way to do that is to stand out visually.<br />
<br />
2. Yep the scroller takes extra space for the thumb.  It's unavoidable.  I've experimented, but there's no way to make any part of the timer overlap the scrollbar.  I might find a way to make it blend in with the background better, or even make it transparent and put something behind it, but technically it'll always take up that extra space.<br />
<br />
3. Screen space again.  This is the same issue.  But I wonder how much space it saves.  Your new bars with their double sliders are twice as wide (or should I say tall) as the old bars.<br />
<br />
By the way, there's no reason that a timer couldn't have both a slider AND a marker.  All it takes is a little transparency, you can have both.<br />
<br />
But in the meantime I'll concentrate on the strengths of this style: visibility.<br />
<br />
One thing you can never do with a non-scrolling timer is have the circle go off-screen.  It always has to be visible so you can place the marker on it.  So I'm thinking of making my timer much wider than the bar.  Then the circle won't even appear on screen until the last quarter (or possibly third) of the time... the timer won't catch your attention at all until time is almost up.<br />
<br />
Second, I'm considering a way to turn a timer off when not using it.  It could be as simple as having an overlapping non-transparent control.  Click in the right place and the timer is (mostly) hidden, click someplace on the timer again and it comes back.  In cases where I have seven different timers but I'm only using two of them, that'd help a lot.<br />
<br />
And I'm still trying to figure out layout boxes.  So far they seem to have some odd restrictions, and don't want to scroll properly, so I haven't been able to use them yet.<br />
<br />
BTW:<br />
It took awhile, but I finally figured out the mathematics that determine which timer widths are suitable.  If you want a timer that A) is any number of seconds (even 1 second), and B) has the same delay for every movement, there are only sixteen possibilities.  1, 2, 4, 8, 5, 10, 20, 25, 40, 50, 100, 125, 200, 250, 500, 1000.  I'm pretty sure I'll settle on 40, 50, 100, 125, 200, or 250.  A few more choices are possible if you're willing to restrict the timer to a multiple of six seconds (seeing as how everything in EQ is done in ticks).</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
